# Detailed key insights table:

| Category | Insight | Value / Metric | Business Implication | 
| -------- | ------- | -------------- | -------------------- |
| **Workforce Trend** | Hiring peaked post‑COVID then contracted sharply | +0.5% (2020→2022); −32% (2022→2024) | Rapid headcount reduction risks capability gaps and knowledge loss |
| **Attrition** | Resignations declined despite hiring drop | −34.6% (2023→2024); Customer Support had 61 resignations in 2024 | Lower churn may reflect hiring freeze or retention measures |
| **Gender & Hiring** |  Female hiring peaked in 2022; Operations hired most women | 4,455 female hires in 2022; 588 in Operations | Strong female representation in Operations; useful for DEI planning |
| **Employee Sentiment** | Satisfaction similar for stayers and leavers | Avg score 3/5 across five year | Engagement programs needed; satisfaction alone not predictive of churn |
|**Tenure & Performance** | Experienced cohort with top performance | 1,221 employees with 4+ years; top score 5/5 | Retention of high performers is a strategic asset |
|**Young Managers** | Inexperienced managers concentrated among young hires | 252 managers <25 years; 206 with only high school education | Potential leadership capability gap; training required |
| **Workload** | Typical and extreme weekly hours | Avg **45** hrs; Min **30** hrs; Max **60** hrs | Risk of burnout at high-hour extremes; workload redistribution needed |
| **Salary Spend** | Operations received peak salary outlay in 2022 | **$7.62M** paid to Operations in 2022 | Operations is a major cost center; review budget allocation |
| **Top Earners** | Many employees at top salary band | 2,679 employees at **$9,000/month** | Large top-pay cohort; assess pay-for-performance alignment |
| **Pay vs Hours Anomalies** |  High pay with low hours and low pay with high hours | 81 employees at $9,000 on 30 hrs; 43 employees at $3,850 on  60 hrs | Pay structure misalignment; equity and fairness issues |
| **Role Pay Range** | Highest and lowest average monthly salaries by role | Engineers **$7,975** (2024); Technicians **$4,444** (Customer Support) | Role-based compensation review recommended |
| **Project Load by Dept** | IT analysts handled most projects; HR managers the fewest | IT analysts **4,782 projects** (2021); HR managers **1,890** (2021) | Resource imbalance across departments |
| **Individual Project Extremes** | High individual project counts concentrated in a few employees | 218 employees handled 49 projects in 2020; 127 in 2024 | Potential over-reliance on high-output individuals |
| **Project vs Hours vs Pay** | Contradictory patterns in productivity and pay | Technician (ID 17986) did 49 projects at 60 hrs for $3,850; 3 employees did 49 projects at 30 hrs for $9,000 | Incentive and productivity measurement issues |
| **Idle High-Hours Staff** | Employees working max hours with no projects | 25 employees at 60 hrs with 0 projects; some paid up to $8,400 | Inefficient resource allocation or misreported activity |
| **Promotion & Training** | Promotions and training correlate with performance | Operations had 1,197 promotions in 2021; 62 employees had 99 training hours and top performance | Training-to-performance linkage is evident |
| **Sick Leave** | Female employees recorded the highest sick leave in 2022 | 4,175 sick leaves in 2022; max 14 days per employee | Health and wellbeing programs may be needed |
| **Overtime** | IT led overtime in 2020 | IT overtime **17,577** hours; max individual overtime **29 hrs** | Overtime hotspots indicate capacity constraints |
| **Rapid Promotions** | Young consultants received accelerated promotions | Two consultants aged 22 and 23 received 2 promotions in 2024 | Fast-track career paths exist; assess fairness and criteria |
| **Gender Pay Parity** | Near parity at top salary band | Females **1,271** vs Males **1,292** at $9,000/month | Top-pay gender balance is roughly equal | 


 


